Cool.

00:03:07.639 --> 00:03:08.639
Cool.

00:03:08.639 --> 00:03:09.639
So that was the demo.

00:03:09.639 --> 00:03:15.440
As you saw, it went from R to a shiny app to Stripe, and then somehow a postcard appeared.

00:03:15.440 --> 00:03:16.440
But how does it work?

00:03:16.440 --> 00:03:17.440
How does it work?

00:03:17.440 --> 00:03:18.440
How does it work?

00:03:18.440 --> 00:03:19.440
There we go.

00:03:19.440 --> 00:03:20.440
How does it work?

00:03:20.440 --> 00:03:21.440
Okay.

00:03:21.440 --> 00:03:22.440
So there's an R package called Gigi IRL.

00:03:22.440 --> 00:03:23.440
That's what you install on your computer and talks to Shiny server.

00:03:23.440 --> 00:03:34.600
And then there's a Shiny server called Gigi IRL server, which does all the work of showing

00:03:34.600 --> 00:03:38.320
the user preview, passing the information to Stripe, fulfilling the postcard via an

00:03:38.320 --> 00:03:42.520
API, so there's a service somewhere I call to make the postcard go, and then sends a

00:03:42.520 --> 00:03:43.880
confirmation email.

00:03:43.960 --> 00:03:48.559
Now, if you think about it, Gigi IRL server should be multiple Shiny apps and plumber

00:03:48.559 --> 00:03:49.559
APIs.

00:03:49.559 --> 00:03:53.839
There's no reason why the fulfillment, why the uploading the information should be done

00:03:53.839 --> 00:03:54.839
via Shiny.

00:03:54.839 --> 00:03:57.800
It's probably better to do that as an API via plumber.

00:03:57.800 --> 00:04:01.800
But for ease of maintenance, I'm like, I really just want one Shiny app to do all of this.

00:04:01.800 --> 00:04:05.360
And by ease of maintenance, I mean I'm super lazy, and I don't want to have to keep a bunch

00:04:05.360 --> 00:04:06.440
of microservices running.

00:04:06.440 --> 00:04:07.699
I just want one.

00:04:07.699 --> 00:04:12.679
But to make this work leads a lot of engineering questions, which I'm going to enumerate now.

00:04:12.679 --> 00:04:16.720
One is how do you pass the plot from R to Shiny?

00:04:16.720 --> 00:04:20.239
If you think about it, Shiny, there's a lot of times where Shiny has data loaded into

00:04:20.239 --> 00:04:21.239
it, right?

00:04:21.239 --> 00:04:23.040
You can read data from a database in Shiny.

00:04:23.040 --> 00:04:25.179
You can press the upload button on Shiny.

00:04:25.179 --> 00:04:29.519
But if you think about it, there's not really an obvious way that if a Shiny server is running,

00:04:29.519 --> 00:04:32.000
how can you programmatically send data to it?

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:33.600
So I don't want it to read data on load.

00:04:33.600 --> 00:04:36.160
I want to just pass the data to a server that's running.

00:04:36.160 --> 00:04:37.640
It may not even have a web page open.

00:04:37.640 --> 00:04:40.200
I just want it to listen for data.

00:04:40.200 --> 00:04:46.160
So the way you would do that in, like, web development land is you do an HTTP post request.

00:04:46.160 --> 00:04:50.720
So an HTTP post request is a way an API or a website receives data.

00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:55.799
So when you hit submit on a website, your browser is doing a post request to the server.

00:04:55.799 --> 00:04:58.000
That should be done with a post request.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:03.160
Shiny does not have a documented ability to listen for post requests.

00:05:03.160 --> 00:05:05.359
Normally only Plumber does that.

00:05:05.359 --> 00:05:06.600
It should have this.

00:05:06.600 --> 00:05:08.320
And that's my call out to RStudio.

00:05:08.320 --> 00:05:09.559
I mean, pause it.

00:05:09.640 --> 00:05:11.320
I think that would be a really great feature.

00:05:11.320 --> 00:05:15.040
The good news is there's actually a number of undocumented ways to do this.

00:05:15.040 --> 00:05:18.640
And so, again, what I'm trying to do is I'm trying to post the image to Shiny.

00:05:18.640 --> 00:05:20.200
So here's the plot I've made.

00:05:20.200 --> 00:05:24.440
And then I want Shiny to come back to me with, okay, here's the ID of that image.

00:05:24.440 --> 00:05:25.399
I'm like, cool, I got the image.

00:05:25.399 --> 00:05:27.559
I'm going to call it FC whatever.

00:05:27.559 --> 00:05:29.279
And then the package is going to be like, okay, cool.

00:05:29.279 --> 00:05:33.839
I'm then going to take the user to the browser website to actually do the preview.

00:05:33.839 --> 00:05:36.279
So this is a back and forth of the post request.

00:05:36.279 --> 00:05:38.839
So there are a number of undocumented ways to do this.

00:05:38.839 --> 00:05:42.600
The way I like the most is you use the brochure package by Colin Fay.

00:05:42.600 --> 00:05:49.720
This is an experimental package that lets you connect multiple Shiny apps together.

00:05:49.720 --> 00:05:51.920
So if you have like three different Shiny apps and you're like, man,

00:05:51.920 --> 00:05:54.119
I really wish all of them were running at once,

00:05:54.119 --> 00:05:57.320
you can bundle them all up into one Shiny app using brochure.

00:05:57.320 --> 00:06:00.040
You can also listen to requests besides get.

00:06:00.040 --> 00:06:03.640
So if you want to have your Shiny app listen for data, not just show webpages,

00:06:03.640 --> 00:06:05.160
brochure will let you do that too.

00:06:05.160 --> 00:06:06.920
So this actually solves two of my problems.

00:06:06.920 --> 00:06:09.079
One, it lets me listen for post data.

00:06:09.079 --> 00:06:12.279
And two, I can actually have a bunch of concurrent Shiny apps,

00:06:12.279 --> 00:06:17.040
one for the order upload, one for the fulfillment, one for the preview.

00:06:17.040 --> 00:06:18.760
It's so new, it doesn't even have a hex sticker.

00:06:18.760 --> 00:06:21.720
It also says all over it, experimental, do not use in production.

00:06:21.720 --> 00:06:23.959
But here I am using in production and it's working great.

00:06:23.959 --> 00:06:25.640
Thanks, Colin.

00:06:25.640 --> 00:06:28.239
If you want to see examples of the other ways that are actually built

00:06:28.239 --> 00:06:32.720
into Shiny to do post request, I have a link at the bottom and you can check it out.

00:06:32.720 --> 00:06:33.359
Cool.

00:06:33.359 --> 00:06:35.480
So how do you show the image preview?

00:06:35.480 --> 00:06:39.000
So once we have the data uploaded into Shiny, how do we show the image?

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:41.679
Well, this is actually just a Shiny app with one button.

00:06:41.679 --> 00:06:44.920
What I do is I have the URL you go to, have the token,

00:06:44.920 --> 00:06:47.640
which is the ID of the particular postcard you uploaded.

00:06:47.640 --> 00:06:52.040
I have that in the URL and then the Shiny app shows a different postcard

00:06:52.040 --> 00:06:54.200
depending on what your token is.

00:06:54.200 --> 00:06:58.559
Now, I put a lot of work into the bootstrap and the CSS to make it all look pretty

00:06:58.559 --> 00:07:01.359
and to get the margins on the postcard right and all that.

00:07:01.359 --> 00:07:04.119
I have a whole separate talk about making your Shiny apps look pretty

00:07:04.119 --> 00:07:06.480
that I gave at ShinyConf 2022.

00:07:06.480 --> 00:07:10.519
So if you want like 45 minutes of hearing about how to make your Shiny apps look pretty,

00:07:10.519 --> 00:07:12.000
I suggest you check out that talk.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:13.600
It was a lot of fun.

00:07:13.600 --> 00:07:14.359
So, okay, cool.

00:07:14.359 --> 00:07:15.679
So we have a Shiny app.

00:07:15.679 --> 00:07:17.559
It shows you the preview of the thing.

00:07:17.559 --> 00:07:19.959
It got the data from a post request from R.

00:07:19.959 --> 00:07:23.480
But how do we then pass the user from Shiny to Stripe, right?

00:07:23.480 --> 00:07:26.600
How do I make that pay and submit button send someone to Stripe?

00:07:26.600 --> 00:07:29.160
I thought this would be the hardest part of the app,

00:07:29.160 --> 00:07:32.760
but it actually was surprisingly easy to make this.

00:07:32.760 --> 00:07:35.559
There are really just two steps in the payment flow.

00:07:35.559 --> 00:07:40.160
First is you need Shiny to send Stripe what is actually in the shopping cart of the user,

00:07:40.160 --> 00:07:41.679
which is called the Stripe session.

00:07:41.679 --> 00:07:43.679
You do this via a post request.

00:07:43.679 --> 00:07:48.679
By the way, it turns out GGIRL, it's like 95% just post requests bouncing around,

00:07:48.679 --> 00:07:49.640
and this is another one.

00:07:49.640 --> 00:07:51.880
It's not the last.

00:07:51.880 --> 00:07:55.440
You then also, once you've posted the cart,

00:07:55.440 --> 00:07:59.279
you then have to have the user go to the Shiny page or the Stripe page.

00:07:59.279 --> 00:08:04.799
So Stripe has a JavaScript API to get users to the appropriate Stripe checkout page.

00:08:04.799 --> 00:08:06.679
I refuse to learn JavaScript.

00:08:06.679 --> 00:08:08.040
I will never do this.

00:08:08.040 --> 00:08:09.880
The good...

00:08:09.880 --> 00:08:11.440
Yeah, I'm not alone here.

00:08:11.440 --> 00:08:13.079
Great.

00:08:13.079 --> 00:08:16.239
The good news is that Shiny makes it very easy, I found out,

00:08:16.239 --> 00:08:18.959
to use other people's JavaScript APIs.

00:08:18.959 --> 00:08:23.600
So what you do is you add tags, $script to the top of your Shiny app

00:08:23.600 --> 00:08:25.600
to load in the JavaScript API,

00:08:25.600 --> 00:08:27.920
and then you Shiny.customMessageHandler

00:08:27.959 --> 00:08:30.959
so that when the action button is pressed for pay and submit,

00:08:30.959 --> 00:08:33.880
it will call that special JavaScript.

00:08:33.880 --> 00:08:35.080
So it's really just two steps.

00:08:35.080 --> 00:08:36.840
And again, if you want to see the particular code,

00:08:36.840 --> 00:08:38.960
you can go to that GGIRL examples repo,

00:08:38.960 --> 00:08:41.559
and you can see an example there.

00:08:41.559 --> 00:08:44.719
So this gets the user from Shiny to Stripe,

00:08:44.719 --> 00:08:49.640
where they presumably pay money because they are excited about a postcard.

00:08:49.640 --> 00:08:51.799
How do you then fulfill the order?

00:08:51.799 --> 00:08:54.400
So how do you have Shiny then listen for Stripe,

00:08:54.400 --> 00:08:56.359
Stripe being like, okay, cool, they paid you money.

00:08:56.359 --> 00:08:58.760
Now we're going to go ahead and make the order.

00:08:58.760 --> 00:09:01.559
So we do this with a POST request.

00:09:01.559 --> 00:09:03.599
So we're going to have Stripe send a POST request

00:09:03.599 --> 00:09:05.440
telling Shiny to order the postcards.

00:09:05.440 --> 00:09:09.080
So if your server is listening for someone else's POST request,

00:09:09.080 --> 00:09:10.679
that is called a webhook.

00:09:10.679 --> 00:09:12.840
It's just a different name for another POST request.

00:09:12.840 --> 00:09:14.919
It's just kind of going in the other direction.

00:09:14.919 --> 00:09:19.200
So we're going to use a webhook saying, hey, order XYZ or FCE6,

00:09:19.200 --> 00:09:21.760
whatever the order number is, has been paid for.

00:09:21.760 --> 00:09:24.679
And to make sure that people just don't know what that URL is

00:09:24.679 --> 00:09:26.880
and spam it to get a million postcards,

00:09:26.880 --> 00:09:29.280
we are going to add keys to ensure that the message

00:09:29.280 --> 00:09:32.200
actually came from Stripe itself.

00:09:32.200 --> 00:09:35.520
So Stripe will then, so Shiny will receive the request

00:09:35.520 --> 00:09:37.039
and be like, okay, cool, the order is placed.

00:09:37.039 --> 00:09:42.080
And then Shiny will call the stuff to send the postcard and send the email.

00:09:42.080 --> 00:09:44.799
So, and this feels like it should be straightforward, right?

00:09:44.799 --> 00:09:47.400
I've already done two or three POST requests as part of this talk.

00:09:47.400 --> 00:09:49.799
This is just another POST request.

00:09:49.799 --> 00:09:51.440
But here's the issue,

00:09:51.440 --> 00:09:56.039
is that Stripe needs to know that the message was received really quickly.

00:09:56.039 --> 00:09:58.039
So if Stripe says the order was confirmed,

00:09:58.039 --> 00:10:00.119
and Stripe doesn't hear right away that the order actually,

00:10:00.119 --> 00:10:02.359
like, you're Apgil, like, cool, we got the order,

00:10:02.359 --> 00:10:04.159
she'll be like, oh my god, they didn't hear it.

00:10:04.159 --> 00:10:05.520
I got to send it again.

00:10:05.520 --> 00:10:07.479
And here's the thing you might know about Shiny,

00:10:07.479 --> 00:10:10.039
is Shiny takes a while when it's running stuff.

00:10:10.039 --> 00:10:13.080
So if you're not, ah, you guys are putting it together.

00:10:13.080 --> 00:10:16.080
Yes, this took me a while, too long to put together.

00:10:16.080 --> 00:10:17.119
But if you're not careful,

00:10:17.119 --> 00:10:20.119
Stripe will ask for the order to be submitted over and over,

00:10:20.119 --> 00:10:22.640
and Shiny will be like, cool, got it, cool, got it, cool, got it.

00:10:22.640 --> 00:10:27.440
And the next thing you know, you have 20 POST cards sent to your house.

00:10:27.440 --> 00:10:30.919
So the trick to solve this is you're going to use Caller package.

00:10:30.919 --> 00:10:34.880
And Caller's a really cool package to run our processes in the background.

00:10:34.880 --> 00:10:37.039
So when you get the order from Stripe,

00:10:37.039 --> 00:10:38.840
you're going to use Caller to send,

00:10:38.840 --> 00:10:41.159
like, actually send the POST card, send the email.

00:10:41.159 --> 00:10:42.799
That's all going to happen in the background,

00:10:42.799 --> 00:10:45.080
so that Shiny can immediately respond to Stripe being like,

00:10:45.080 --> 00:10:47.239
yeah, cool, we got it, and not be bogged down

00:10:47.239 --> 00:10:52.919
by the time it takes to submit the POST card order and send the email.

00:10:52.919 --> 00:10:55.359
I love using Caller so much from learning this

00:10:55.359 --> 00:10:58.640
that I actually made a whole talk about using R in parallel,

00:10:58.640 --> 00:10:59.440
which is a separate thing.

00:10:59.440 --> 00:11:02.640
If you want to learn about that, I have a separate talk for this.

00:11:02.640 --> 00:11:04.960
And if you actually want to just see the code that does this,

00:11:04.960 --> 00:11:07.440
again, ggirlexamples has that.

00:11:07.440 --> 00:11:09.159
So to actually fulfill the order,

00:11:09.159 --> 00:11:13.320
I needed to use Caller to run R in the background.

00:11:13.320 --> 00:11:14.719
And then to order the POST cards,

00:11:14.719 --> 00:11:17.080
it turns out there are, like, tons of companies out there

00:11:17.080 --> 00:11:20.799
that will make APIs that if you hit that API with a POST request,

00:11:20.799 --> 00:11:23.559
with the message, the address, and the front of the POST card,

00:11:23.559 --> 00:11:25.239
they will ship it to that location.

00:11:25.239 --> 00:11:28.640
This makes sense because you get lots of POST cards in the mail for advertisements.

00:11:28.640 --> 00:11:31.200
So lots of companies use these services.

00:11:31.200 --> 00:11:32.320
Two problems here.

00:11:32.320 --> 00:11:34.479
One, it takes a while to ship POST cards, right?

00:11:34.479 --> 00:11:36.239
It takes, like, two weeks to ship POST cards.

00:11:36.239 --> 00:11:39.200
So it takes a while before you actually get the POST card back.

00:11:39.200 --> 00:11:41.760
And two, companies that are sending millions of POST cards

00:11:41.760 --> 00:11:43.119
to every person in the country

00:11:43.119 --> 00:11:45.280
don't care really how good the POST cards look,

00:11:45.280 --> 00:11:46.359
as long as they're cheap.

00:11:46.359 --> 00:11:49.760
So it took forever for me to find a service that was actually good.

00:11:49.760 --> 00:11:51.320
And so it took two weeks, and I didn't like it.

00:11:51.320 --> 00:11:52.599
And two weeks, and I didn't like it.

00:11:52.599 --> 00:11:54.440
And in fact, if you see over there,

00:11:54.440 --> 00:11:56.799
if you see in this image on the presentation,

00:11:56.799 --> 00:11:58.080
it looks kind of blurry.

00:11:58.080 --> 00:11:59.840
It looks kind of like JPEG artifacts.

00:11:59.840 --> 00:12:02.840
Like, this was like a Facebook meme that got sent to you too many times.

00:12:02.840 --> 00:12:04.719
That was not this picture I uploaded.

00:12:04.719 --> 00:12:07.119
That's what it actually looked like on the POST card.

00:12:07.119 --> 00:12:11.880
And that is beneath the dignity of ggplot2plots.

00:12:11.880 --> 00:12:13.520
So I had to spend a while.

00:12:13.520 --> 00:12:14.919
By far, this is the longest part

00:12:14.919 --> 00:12:17.039
because I had to spend a while until I find a printing service

00:12:17.039 --> 00:12:19.159
that was actually good.

00:12:19.159 --> 00:12:22.559
To send the confirmation emails, this is actually pretty easy.

00:12:22.559 --> 00:12:25.559
There's a package Blastula, which can send those emails.

00:12:25.559 --> 00:12:27.559
So all I had to do to put the preview in the email

00:12:27.559 --> 00:12:28.880
is I wanted to resize it

00:12:28.880 --> 00:12:31.679
because those images had to be very large for the printer,

00:12:31.679 --> 00:12:34.799
and I wanted to resize them so they weren't like five megs in your inbox.

00:12:34.799 --> 00:12:37.280
So I used the package ImageMagick to resize them

00:12:37.280 --> 00:12:39.400
and get the right margins and everything.

00:12:39.400 --> 00:12:42.479
But sometimes there would be an error in the fulfillment.

00:12:42.479 --> 00:12:45.039
So not only did I have to send an email to the users,

00:12:45.039 --> 00:12:47.840
but if anything ever goes wrong, I wanted to make sure I caught it,

00:12:47.840 --> 00:12:49.479
so I'd have to send an email to me.

00:12:49.479 --> 00:12:52.239
And once in a while, the email system would have an error in emailing,

00:12:52.239 --> 00:12:53.760
so I had to email about that too.

00:12:53.760 --> 00:12:56.880
It was a real web of emails being sent.

00:12:56.880 --> 00:12:59.919
So lastly, how do you actually deploy it?

00:12:59.919 --> 00:13:01.719
So I needed the server to actually be...

00:13:01.719 --> 00:13:07.039
That ggirl server, the Shiny app, had to be continuously living somewhere.

00:13:07.039 --> 00:13:10.280
So the place it is currently running is on Saturn Cloud.

00:13:10.280 --> 00:13:12.520
So Saturn Cloud, I'm the chief product officer of the company.

00:13:12.520 --> 00:13:16.000
And so it was really nice for this... I know, it's a...

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:18.320
I'm advertising.

00:13:18.320 --> 00:13:21.119
So it was actually very nice because I had two RStudio servers

00:13:21.119 --> 00:13:23.200
running in Saturn Cloud in the cloud.

00:13:23.200 --> 00:13:24.919
So one was the one I actually was showing you,

00:13:24.919 --> 00:13:28.719
which is how I did the development of the Shiny package in RStudio in a browser.

00:13:28.719 --> 00:13:33.159
But I also had a RStudio running for developing the Shiny backend.

00:13:33.159 --> 00:13:36.760
And I actually had two Shiny servers running on Saturn Cloud.

00:13:36.799 --> 00:13:40.559
One, the actual server, the Shiny server you saw, the production one,

00:13:40.559 --> 00:13:43.159
but as well as a development one that I could test with

00:13:43.159 --> 00:13:46.280
and use like fake credit cards and it would fake send emails.

00:13:46.280 --> 00:13:48.520
So I ended up having four systems all running on Saturn Cloud,

00:13:48.520 --> 00:13:50.359
which is pretty nice and easy.

00:13:50.359 --> 00:13:53.159
And most importantly, I beta tested this with a bunch of people

00:13:53.159 --> 00:13:54.679
to make sure it worked first.

00:13:54.679 --> 00:13:58.159
And that took a while and helped me really iron out some usability issues.

00:13:58.159 --> 00:14:00.840
And that was really nice as well.

00:14:00.840 --> 00:14:02.719
So wrapping it all up.

00:14:02.719 --> 00:14:06.840
ggirl is a cool package for ordering cool stuff.

00:14:06.840 --> 00:14:10.080
This required me to do a bunch of things that I assumed might be true in Shiny,

00:14:10.080 --> 00:14:12.039
but I didn't actually know, and it turns out it is,

00:14:12.039 --> 00:14:14.559
which includes receiving data from an R package,

00:14:14.559 --> 00:14:18.719
listening for post requests, sending and receiving Stripe API calls,

00:14:18.719 --> 00:14:21.679
and spawning background processes that didn't slow down

00:14:21.679 --> 00:14:23.919
the Shiny responsiveness.

00:14:23.919 --> 00:14:29.880
I forgot to mention at the beginning that not only can you send GG postcards,

00:14:29.880 --> 00:14:31.679
but you can also order art prints for your walls,

00:14:31.679 --> 00:14:33.599
which people have used for graduation presents and stuff,

00:14:33.599 --> 00:14:34.359
which is really cool.

00:14:34.359 --> 00:14:36.320
And people use, oh, by the way, people use GG postcards

00:14:36.320 --> 00:14:37.960
for baby announcements and stuff.

00:14:37.960 --> 00:14:40.679
People get really clever uses for these, so it's a lot of fun.

00:14:40.679 --> 00:14:42.159
And there's GG watercolor, which is just,

00:14:42.159 --> 00:14:44.919
I hand-paint a watercolor for you if you want it.

00:14:44.919 --> 00:14:49.320
So you can install the package with the ggnolist, ggirl...

00:14:49.320 --> 00:14:49.880
That's not me.

00:14:49.880 --> 00:14:51.640
ggnolist, ggirl.

00:14:51.640 --> 00:14:54.440
You can actually, if you want to make one of your own souvenir commemorative

00:14:54.440 --> 00:14:56.919
